SIMPLE: surmount
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Surmount
<hw>Sur*mount"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Surmounted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Surmounting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sourmounten</ets>,
OF. <ets>surmonter</ets>, <ets>sormonter</ets>, F. <ets>surmonter</ets>;
<ets>sur</ets> over + <ets>monter</ets> to mount. See <er>Sur-</er>, and
<er>Mount</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To rise above;
to be higher than; to overtop.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mountains of Olympus, Athos, and Atlas, overreach and
<qex>surmount</qex> all winds and clouds.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To conquer; to overcome; <as>as, to
<ex>surmount</ex> difficulties or obstacles</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To surpass; to exceed.</def>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>surmounts</qex> the reach⟦br⟧
Of human sense I shall delineate.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To conquer; overcome; vanquish; subdue; surpass;
exceed.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surmountable</ent>⟦br⟧
